<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,547,1222]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,325,979,1006]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Discussion</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rasetti" authorityYear="1946" box="[339,516,980,1006]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nasuta">
<emphasis box="[339,516,980,1006]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Blountia nasuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pl. 12, figs 1–6) resembles 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[834,1092,980,1006]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Maryvillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[834,1092,980,1006]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Maryvillia triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a roughly triangular anterior cranidial margin, and a pygidium is also triangular in outline (Pl. 12, figs 7–12). However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rasetti" authorityYear="1946" box="[1252,1358,1016,1042]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nasuta">
<emphasis box="[1252,1269,1016,1041]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1283,1358,1016,1041]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">nasuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in having a longer frontal area (accounting for 37% cranidial length, versus 28% in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[1098,1270,1052,1078]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Maryvillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[1098,1270,1052,1078]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">M. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with a longer preglabellar field (occupying 46% of frontal area, versus 30%), and a flat, rather than concave border. The facial sutures of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rasetti" authorityYear="1946" box="[268,374,1124,1149]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nasuta">
<emphasis box="[268,374,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">B. nasuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
diverge forward from the palpebral lobes, whereas the anterior branches of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[1224,1395,1124,1150]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Maryvillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[1224,1395,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">M. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are nearly parallel. The pygidium of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rasetti" authorityYear="1946" box="[520,626,1160,1186]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nasuta">
<emphasis box="[520,537,1160,1185]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[551,626,1160,1185]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">nasuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is noticeably flatter (e.g., compare Pl. 12, figs 7. 9, 12 and Pl. 25, figs 2, 3, 5), with a shorter axis and longer (sag.) border.
</paragraph>
